          "validation_ok": true,
          "errors": [],
          "repaired": false,
          "latency_ms": 5715,
          "unit_kind": "paragraph"
        },
        "text": "EK supports the overall objective of ensuring a fair and competitive digital environment for both consumers and businesses in the EU. However, we stress that any new regulatory initiative must be based on a clear legislative need, robust impact assessments, and a thorough evaluation of the effectiveness and sufficiency of existing legislation before considering new rules. Any new regulation should be technology-neutral and principle-based to ensure predictability, encourage innovation, and support a positive investment climate.",
        "chunk_meta": {
          "section_id": "s2",
          "section_path": [
            "Public consultation on the Digital Fairness Act (DFA)",
            "Call for evidence / Feedback"
          ],
          "span": null,
          "chunk_quality": "ok",
          "chunk_word_count": 75,
          "char_len": 533
        }
      },
      {
        "para_id": "p4",
        "items": [],
        "meta": {
          "skipped": false,
          "skip_reason": null,
          "validation_ok": true,
          "errors": [],
          "repaired": false,
          "latency_ms": 8049,
          "unit_kind": "paragraph"
        },
        "text": "We emphasize that the primary focus should be on the effective enforcement and guidance of the current regulatory framework - including the Digital Services Act (DSA), Digital Markets Act (DMA), Unfair Commercial Practices Directive (UCPD), AI Act, the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), and the recently revised General Product Safety Regulation (GPSR) - rather than introducing new overlapping or duplicative rules. New regulation should only be considered if a genuine legislative gap is identified, not merely due to shortcomings in enforcement. Regulation must be clear, targeted, and proportionate, avoiding unnecessary administrative burdens, especially for SMEs. Simplification, clarity, and coherence of the regulatory landscape are essential goals. Self-regulation should be promoted wherever possible as a complement to legislation, fostering consumer trust and a level playing field among competitors.",
        "chunk_meta": {
          "section_id": "s2",
          "section_path": [
            "Public consultation on the Digital Fairness Act (DFA)",
            "Call for evidence / Feedback"
          ],
          "span": null,
